---
title: Sequencing Events
description: Learn the connectors that order events in a story so your narration flows step by step
level: conversational
time: 25 minutes
---

# Grammar: Ordering the Story

## Putting Events in Order

Sequencing connectors order events relative to each other and show how a story moves from one moment to the next. The simplest ones are primero, luego, después, finalmente. They work, but they sound like a recipe.

Primero salí de casa, luego tomé el autobús.
  First I left home, then I took the bus.

## Sequencing Across Time

These more natural connectors place events along a timeline and suggest how much time passed between them. They're the backbone of a flowing narration.

Al principio todo estaba tranquilo.
  At first everything was calm.

Poco después, algo cambió.
  Shortly after, something changed.

Eventualmente, entendí lo que estaba pasando.
  Eventually, I understood what was happening.

# Grammar: Matching Connectors to Tenses

## When Two Things Happen at Once

To show two actions happening at the same time, use mientras, cuando, al mismo tiempo, or a medida que. These pair with the imperfecto — the tense for ongoing background action.

Mientras caminaba, escuché un ruido.
  While I was walking, I heard a noise.

A medida que avanzaba, me sentía más nervioso.
  As I went on, I felt more nervous.

## When One Thing Happens Right After Another

To show an action that happens immediately after another, use en cuanto, apenas, or tan pronto como. These pair with the pretérito — the quick, completed action that moves the plot forward.

En cuanto llegué, empezó la reunión.
  As soon as I arrived, the meeting started.

Apenas lo vi, supe que algo estaba mal.
  The moment I saw him, I knew something was wrong.

# Vocabulary: Basic Sequencing

primero
  first
  [pree-MEH-roh]

luego
  then / next
  [LWEH-goh]

después
  after / afterward
  [dehs-PWEHS]

finalmente
  finally
  [fee-nahl-MEHN-teh]

# Vocabulary: Natural Sequencing

al principio
  at first / in the beginning
  [ahl preen-SEE-pee-oh]

al inicio
  at the start
  [ahl ee-NEE-see-oh]

no mucho después
  not long after
  [noh MOO-choh dehs-PWEHS]

con el tiempo
  over time
  [kohn ehl tee-EHM-poh]

eventualmente
  eventually
  [eh-behn-twahl-MEHN-teh]

al final
  in the end
  [ahl fee-NAHL]

# Vocabulary: Simultaneous Actions

mientras
  while
  [mee-EHN-trahs]

cuando
  when
  [KWAHN-doh]

al mismo tiempo
  at the same time
  [ahl MEES-moh tee-EHM-poh]

a medida que
  as / as it progressed
  [ah meh-DEE-dah keh]

# Vocabulary: Immediate Actions

en cuanto
  as soon as
  [ehn KWAHN-toh]

apenas
  the moment / barely
  [ah-PEH-nahs]

tan pronto como
  as soon as
  [tahn PROHN-toh KOH-moh]

# Phrases: Sequencing in Action

Al principio todo estaba tranquilo.
  At first everything was calm.
  [ahl preen-SEE-pee-oh]

Poco después, algo cambió.
  Shortly after, something changed.
  [POH-koh dehs-PWEHS]

Eventualmente, entendí lo que estaba pasando.
  Eventually, I understood what was happening.
  [eh-behn-twahl-MEHN-teh]

En cuanto llegué, empezó la reunión.
  As soon as I arrived, the meeting started.
  [ehn KWAHN-toh yeh-GEH ehm-peh-SOH]

Mientras caminaba, escuché un ruido.
  While I was walking, I heard a noise.
  [mee-EHN-trahs kah-mee-NAH-bah]

